<p>Comments are not an official standard, although some parsers support C++-style comments. One that I use is <a href="https://github.com/open-source-parsers/jsoncpp" rel="noreferrer">JsonCpp</a>. In the examples there is this one:</p>

<pre><code>// Configuration options
{
    // Default encoding for text
    "encoding" : "UTF-8",

    // Plug-ins loaded at start-up
    "plug-ins" : [
        "python",
        "c++",
        "ruby"
        ],

    // Tab indent size
    "indent" : { "length" : 3, "use_space": true }
}
</code></pre>

<p><a href="http://www.jsonlint.com" rel="noreferrer">jsonlint</a> does not validate this. So comments are a parser specific extension and not standard.</p>

<p>Another parser is <a href="https://json5.org/" rel="noreferrer">JSON5</a>.</p>

<p>An alternative to JSON <a href="https://github.com/toml-lang/toml" rel="noreferrer">TOML</a>.</p>

<p>A further alternative is <a href="https://www.npmjs.com/package/jsonc" rel="noreferrer">jsonc</a>.</p>
